title: For Sale:  7.62x25 Ammo - 350 Rounds Polish Military, Five 70 Round Boxes
postcontent:
Here are 350 rounds of a Polish Military 7.62x25 ammunition.

It's brass case with a Full Metal Jacket bullet. The jacket material is actually a two part deal with a thick steel inner jacket covered by a thinner copper outer jacket, and that's why this ammo attracts a magnet. It's probably also a part of why this stuff penetrates like crazy. The truth is that this round's penetration ability comes from a combination of very high velocity coupled with a small diameter bullet that has a thick steel inner jacket. There really isn't anything quite like the 7.62x25 in our American pistol cartridge lineup. 

This Polish ammo also always seemed to shoot a little cleaner than other surplus ammo for me, and it's sure to fire. It is corrosive primed so cleaning your firearm is a must and you'll never have any problems.

Then the last thing is that this ammo is noticeably hotter than any other surplus or commercial ammo I've tried. This may be due to the fact that this ammo was designed to function properly in the Pole's sub-machine guns. If you shoot it side by side with anything else I think you'll notice the difference too. I've shot this same ammo in a number of CZ52's and various TOK pistols without issue, however all of my firearms were in tip top condition. So you must be sure your firearms are in top shape too before firing this ammo or any other military grade ammo in them. When in doubt seek the advice of a professional gunsmith.

THIS LISTING IS FOR 5 SEALED 70 ROUND BOXES FOR A TOTAL OF 350 ROUNDS. THE LOOSE ROUNDS SHOWN ARE FROM AN OPEN BOX AND ARE NOT INCLUDED IN THIS LISTING.

Price is $125 with pick up in the Brandon area or I can ship via UPS ground for the actual cost.

Unfortunately no sales or shipping to: AK, CA, CT, Chicago, DC, HI, MA, NJ, or NY. IL must provide copy of FOID card. You must be at least 21 to purchase this ammo.

title: For Sale:  BROWNING ~ SUPERPOSED B-25 B2G GRADE...29.5 IC/IM V 28 GAUGE
postcontent: a beautiful high-grade FN/Browning shotgun! This is a Superposed B-25 that was manufactured in Belgium in the FN Custom Shop. This is a 28-gauge gun that features the "B2G" level engraving pattern designed by Master Engraver, Louis Vranken in 1967. The silver/grey coin finished receiver features a pair of ducks on the right and a pair of pheasants on the left with plenty of scroll on the borders, bottom of receiver and trigger guard. The engraving on this example is reversed to the standard layout, shows exceptional detail, and is signed by FN engraver Pierre Lallemand. The barrels measure 29-1/2" in length, have 2-3/4" chambers, and are choked Improved Modified over Improved Cylinder (the previous owner had Briley Manufacturing open the bottom choke from IM to IC, a very sensible modification). It has the single-selective trigger, automatic ejectors, and non-automatic safety. The oil finished wood shows very attractive figure, the buttstock with the round-knob configuration and the forend with graceful schnable tip. There is a "Decelerator" pad installed for a LOP measuring 14-3/8". The butt shows standard right-hand cast-off, Drop @ Comb is 1-1/2", and Drop @ Heel is 2". Weight is 6-pounces, 8-ounces. Condition is excellent and this gun shows only very light use. The original metal finish rates 98% with only a tiny amount of blue wear to the bottom barrel where the forend slide during assembly/disassembly. There is no rust or any pitting. The stocks are in excellent condition as well with a couple of very minor handling marks and I'd grade the wood at 98% as well.

title: For Trade:  Sig P938 Equinox and Kahr CW40 with CT
postcontent:
I have a Sig Sauer P938 Equinox and a Kahr CW40 with a Crimson Trace Laser I want to trade for a Ultra Series Kimber. 

The Sig P938 Equinox is a Custom Shop sig sauer with the Custom Shop logo etched in the brushed finish from the factory. I am the original owner. It has maybe 50 rounds through it. It is a recent model, not one of the early ones that had issues. This one fires HP and FMJ flawlessly. It comes with the factory hard case, two mags (one extended) and four holsters. The holsters are a very nice Desantis Pocket Holster with shield accessory, Galco leather IWB, Alien Gear Cloak Tuck 2.0  Hybrid, and an Uncle Mikes IWB I bought when I bought the gun before I ordered the nice ones. I have large hands and shoot something a little bigger better, but this is a match grade little gun that packs a lot of firepower and can reach out with accuracy. It has siglite night sights and the front one is fiber optic as well giving the sights a nice daytime white and green dot contrast and all bright green at night. The grips are Blackwood and are beautiful on the gun. Gun is like new.

The Kahr CW40 is also a nice gun and is my preferred IWB carry gun. I have had Sub Compact and Compact guns from glock, S&W, Springfield, etc. and this one is thinner, lighter, and is more accurate to me than all of them. I got used to the combat sights quickly and the laser is dead on at 15 yards which I don't usually like to use, but on this gun with CT it is very natural feeling. I prefer the Sig for pocket carry, but this gun is capable of that and is very comfortable IWB. It is in great condition, and it comes with two extra mags (three total), some good .40 ammo (HP and FMJ) and an IWB holster. Hard case and paperwork also included. There are mixed reviews on this gun, but if you look closely and do research it is due to improper reassembly after take down and this one has been done correctly. Thus it is 100% reliable with no FTF, FTE, etc. I have at least 200 rounds through it with no problems. It is a clean gun that I trust. It is a double action gun but has a very clean and very light single action feeling trigger, just longer than a single action but just as light. I usually do not hit well with a double action, but I do great with this one. I also have an Alien Gear Cloak Tuck 2.0 for this gun as well special made for the Crimson Trace laser, but I am going to keep it unless I get a nice holster in return. These holsters have a 1.5 month wait and free exchanges for life. I will include it though if I receive a holster in return.

The reason I want to trade is because I have large hands and I wanted the smallest and nicest 1911 platform possible (Sig P938 Equinox) but I think that with my large hands that I should go up one size. I am content keeping it as the world's nicest pocket gun if no trade occurs, but I am also willing to make a deal. The Kahr I got on trade but kept it because I liked it, but I am willing to let it go as well for the right gun.

*I am located in Auburn and will meet 1/2 way. More pics of either gun upon request.
* Black Talons in Sig mags are not incliuded.
*Gun I trade for must be as nice as mine (like new) and come with factory equipment.

title: For Sale:  2 Colt Navy cap and ball replica's
postcontent:
Hello All;

Up for sale I have 2 Colt Navy cap and ball revolvers and miscl black powder accessories. I have one replica C&B revolver, and while its fun I have no use for 3.

I got these two and accessories as a part of a larger lot, so I don't know much about their history, nor am I am expert in these guns so I may be off on a few things. Of I am let me know and I will edit accordingly. While not an expert I do have enough knowledge to work one of these things, and will describe both guns as well as I can.

Top gun in the photo: This is really what I am selling, the rest just sort of goes with it. This is a CVA Colt Navy(unsure of year). It is in very good condition and operates flawlessly, very smooth and tight. You can't really see it in the photo, but the cylinder is engraved, nothing fancy, but it is cool looking.

Lower gun in the photo: This gun is likely not shootable in its present condition. The pin that holds it together is slightly loose enough to leave a small gap between the cylinder and the barrel. Other than the loose pin the revolver operates very smooth. This gun was obviously used significantly more than than the one above and it shows in the appearance. I would say fair at best. This gun may only be good for its parts. This one is a Pietta.

There will also be an ammo can full of everything you need to shoot the guns, and a bunch of stuff you don't need too. Unfortunately it is all a package deal though. There are plenty of caps, the wadding, balls, plenty of powder, a couple powder horns, and some other stuff for a larger caliber musket. I think the only thing you would want to buy is a powder measure, unless you already have one.

There is also an additional Cylinder in the ammo can that will work for either gun.

I have tried to cover as much as I can, but if I left something out please feel free to ask. I will answer as best as possible and send anymore photos you might want. Thanks for looking and have a nice day!

(Note: please disregard the the populated information from the site.  There were no options for what these are so I had to pick the closest option)

-Ben
